ency. Reading d'Urfé, Descartes, La Fontaine, Sévigné, Molière, and Racine through the lens of idolatry reveals heretofore hidden aspects of their work, all while demonstrating the link between the emergent autonomy of literature and philosophy and the confessional conflicts that dominated the period. In so doing, Professor McClure illustrates how religion can become a source of interpretive complexity, and how this dynamism can and should be taken into account in early modern French studies and beyond. ELLEN MCCLURE is Associate Professor of History and French, University of Illinois at Chicago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aFrench Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aConfessional Conflicts.  aD'Urfé.  aDescartes.  aDivine.  aFractured Relationship.  aHuman Agency.  aHuman.  aIdeological Violence.  aIdolatry.  aLa Fontaine.  aLegitimacy.  aLogic of Idolatry.  aMolière.  aPolitical.  aRacine.  aReligious Polemics.  aSeventeenth-Century French Literature.  aSévigné.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446892?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446892/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles